[Gemini]: The code snippet confirms the initial hypothesis. The `FileInput.value_from_datadict` method uses `files.get(name)`. When dealing with file uploads in Django, `request.FILES` (which is passed as the `files` argument) is a `MultiValueDict`. Using the `.get()` method on a `MultiValueDict` will only return the *last* value for a given key if multiple values are submitted. To access all uploaded files for a field, `files.getlist(name)` should be used.

This means that if a user uploads multiple files to a field that uses `FileInput`, only the last file will be processed and validated by the form, while the others are ignored. This can lead to a validation bypass if an attacker uploads a malicious file first, followed by a valid one.

The standard `FileInput` widget does not render the `multiple` HTML attribute by default. However, a developer can easily add this attribute to the widget's `attrs`. A more common widget for file uploads is `ClearableFileInput`, which inherits from `FileInput`. I will now examine its implementation to see if it has the same vulnerability. I'll search for the `ClearableFileInput` class definition in `django/forms/widgets.py`.

